#  Changelog v2.5.35 (FortiLink ISL cabled to aggregate names, not the port):
#   - The link between the two FortiSwitches (169.254.1.2 S224EP <-> 169.254.1.3
#     S124FN) landed on each switch's FortiLink TRUNK interface -- which FortiOS
#     names after the PEER's serial (4FNTF23000240-0 / 4EPTF19005531-0) -- so the
#     cable looked backwards/wrong. But each switch reports the OTHER end as the
#     real physical port (both say port23).
#   - Fix: when pairing the two halves of a link, a side's own local port is used
#     only if it is a real physical port; a serial-derived aggregate/trunk name
#     (detected by a long embedded digit run) is replaced with the physical port
#     the peer reports for that end. Result: S224EP:port23 <-> S124FN:port23.
#     Normal links (office-sw:Port  1 <-> S224EP:port1) are unaffected. Validated
#     against both FortiSwitches' real LLDP.
#   - On the next 1->9, the prune step removes the old aggregate-named cable
#     (its interface is no longer in the kept set) and creates the port23 one.
#     The now-empty 4FNTF.../4EPTF... interfaces remain as cosmetic orphans.
#
#  Changelog v2.5.34 (cabling: reciprocal links collided -> wrong/uplink ports):
#   - Symptom: after 2.5.33, cables on the switch processed FIRST (169.254.1.2)
#     looked right, but the others showed neighbor-abbreviated/'uplink' ports.
#     Cause: each physical link is advertised from BOTH ends with DIFFERENT port
#     names (S224EP:port1 vs office-sw:'Port  1'; S224EP calls office-sw's port
#     '1'). The per-device pass created the first end's cable, then the second
#     end's POST hit an already-occupied termination and failed, leaving the
#     interface named by the neighbor's abbreviation.
#   - Fix: cables are now generated GLOBALLY and deduplicated. The plan emits a
#     top-level 'cables' list: the two halves of each link are paired (by device,
#     with reciprocal correlation) and emitted ONCE, each end under its OWN local
#     port name. One-sided links (neighbor not scanned this run) fall back to the
#     reported remote port; unmanaged neighbors are skipped.
#   - Writer consumes plan.cables (after all devices exist), reconciling one
#     cable per link and pruning per touched device. nb_reconcile_cable now
#     inspects BOTH endpoints: exact match -> no-op; a stale lldp-auto cable on
#     either end (e.g. the bad 2.5.33 'office-sw:1') is removed so the correct
#     cable forms; a manual cable is respected (skip). This self-heals the
#     earlier wrong cables on the next sync. Validated: dedup on the real multi-
#     switch capture (5 clean cables, each end its own port), and reconcile
#     decisions (no-op / replace / skip-manual).
#   - NOTE: empty interfaces left by the 2.5.33 run (e.g. office-sw:'1') remain
#     as cosmetic orphans; the cable moves to the correct port. Delete the empty
#     ones by hand if desired.
#
#  Changelog v2.5.33 (cabling reported success but created nothing):
#   - First live run logged 'LLDP cables created/replaced: 15' but NetBox got
#     zero cables. Cause: nb_create_cable ended in '>/dev/null 2>&1 || true', so
#     a rejected POST was silently treated as success. The rejection itself was
#     almost certainly the tag-write form (tags:["lldp-auto"]) -- the one part
#     that had never run against a live NetBox.
#   - Fixes:
#       * Tool-managed cables are now marked by a version-proof 'lldp-auto:'
#         LABEL prefix (a plain string NetBox cannot reject). The tag is still
#         attempted for UI filtering, but if the tagged POST fails we retry
#         WITHOUT the tag -- tagging never blocks cable creation again.
#       * nb_create_cable now captures the response, returns real success/failure
#         (the cable id), and log_warns the actual NetBox error instead of hiding
#         it. The 'created/replaced' count and per-cable log line now reflect
#         what truly landed.
#       * reconcile + prune detect a tool cable by tag OR label prefix, so
#         management survives whether or not tagging took. Manual cables (no
#         marker) are still never touched.
#   - Validated: payload JSON, and detection across tag-only / label-only /
#     manual. Re-run option 9: cables should now appear (carrying the lldp-auto:
#     label), and a second run should report 0 created (idempotent).
#
#  Changelog v2.5.32 (LLDP cabling INTO NetBox via option 9 -- tagged reconcile):
#   - The single writer now syncs switch cabling, closing the loop: the goal was
#     correct cabling IN NetBox, not just a switchport_*.json dump. Previously
#     only the legacy raw sync made cables, using the 'local port unknown ->
#     uplink-<neighbor>' placeholder (the wrong-cable bug); option 9 made none.
#   - Plan generator emits per-device lldp_links {local_port, neighbor,
#     remote_port} from the scan's lldp_neighbors (which now carry the real
#     local port), dropping self-referential entries. --dry-run lists every
#     cable it would touch. Validated against the live capture: 10 links,
#     reciprocal FortiSwitch trunk kept, local ports real (port1/g8), no uplink-X.
#   - Writer pass 2 (after all devices exist, so neighbors resolve): for each
#     link it ensures the REAL local + remote interfaces, resolves the neighbor
#     device (exact name -> domain-stripped -> serial; unmanaged neighbors are
#     skipped), and RECONCILES a cable tagged 'lldp-auto':
#       * missing -> create   * correct -> leave   * moved -> delete+recreate
#       * port dropped from LLDP -> prune   * manual (untagged) cable -> never touch
#     This answers the cable-change question: a moved cable self-corrects instead
#     of leaving a stale link, and hand-made cables are safe. Reciprocal links
#     collapse to one cable (second pass finds it already correct).
#   - Decision logic unit-tested (create/leave/replace/skip/prune). NOTE: the
#     NetBox tag-write form (tags:["lldp-auto"]) and cable-termination JSON
#     shape are exercised live for the first time -- run option 9 --dry-run, then
#     a real sync, and confirm the lldp-auto cables land on the right ports.
