#  Changelog v2.5.28 (plan crash: TypeError None < str when building clusters):
#   - Option 9 aborted with "'<' not supported between instances of 'NoneType'
#     and 'str'" at sorted(clusters). Cause: a VM whose owning Hyper-V host
#     record came through with a null ip AND null hostname resolved to a null
#     cluster (vm_cluster = host_name or host_ip -> None), which was added to
#     the cluster set and then could not be sorted against the real names.
#   - Fix: an unattributed VM now falls back to an 'Unclustered' bucket instead
#     of None, so it still syncs (the writer creates the cluster and assigns the
#     VM by name); sorted() additionally drops any falsy cluster defensively.
#     Before this, such a VM both crashed the plan and -- had it gotten further
#     -- would have been skipped with 'no cluster for VM'.
#
#  Changelog v2.5.27 (VM IPs blocked by stale device IPs -- the real 'did nothing'):
#   - Why re-running still left VMs with no IP: earlier buggy runs created the
#     VM IPs as DEVICE addresses with a /32 mask (e.g. 192.168.0.160/32). The
#     writer assigns the VM's IP as /24, and NetBox enforce_unique treats
#     .160/24 and .160/32 as the same host -> the POST is rejected, so the VM
#     got no IP and the stale device kept it. (The 2.5.26 ARP persistence was
#     fine; this was a writer/NetBox-state collision downstream of it.)
#   - Fix: nb_add_vm_ip and nb_add_ip now look up an existing address by HOST
#     (any mask) via ?address=<ip>, which matches regardless of prefix. A found
#     object is PATCHed -- reassigned onto the VM interface (or device) and
#     re-masked to the intended prefix -- instead of POSTing a conflicting
#     duplicate. So a stale device-held /32 is MOVED onto the VM.
#   - This means a wipe is no longer required: re-running option 9 now pulls the
#     VM IPs off the stale device shells and onto the VMs. (A wipe still gives
#     the tidiest result by removing the now-empty device shells.)
#
#  Changelog v2.5.26 (VM IPs: persist router/firewall ARP so they stop vanishing):
#   - ROOT CAUSE of VMs losing their IP (and the IP reappearing as a phantom
#     device): VM IPs are resolved by matching the VM's vNIC MAC against the
#     router/firewall ARP tables (VM MAC -> ARP IP). That data is authoritative
#     but VOLATILE -- an ARP entry can be absent for a single scan (aging, an
#     SNMP timeout on the gateway, a router not answering that run). When the
#     entry is missing, the VM gets no IP and the discovered IP falls out to a
#     standalone device. Verified against a real capture: every affected VM IP
#     (.160/.214/.235/.190/.5/.30) was present in the ARP with the exact VM MAC
#     when the fold worked, and absent when it didn't.
#   - Fix: the reconciler now persists the learned IP<->MAC map to
#     discovery/ip_mac_cache.json and merges it on every run -- the current scan
#     always wins, history only fills gaps. So once an IP<->MAC is seen, a VM
#     keeps its IP through scans where the ARP entry transiently disappears.
#     The fold still requires the VM to exist in the current inventory, so a
#     stale cache entry cannot invent a VM. Tested worst-case (all ARP +
#     neighbor + guest IPs stripped): all 6 VM IPs recovered, 0 lost.
#
#  Changelog v2.5.25 (memory_gb: stop flip-flopping the type -- self-heal):
#   - The memory_gb custom field had been bounced between text and integer
#     across builds; once it holds a value NetBox refuses to recast it, so a
#     PATCH of its type silently failed and every run kept 400'ing that one
#     field (the resilient per-field patch logged 'memory_gb rejected').
#   - Fix: nb_ensure_custom_field now DELETES and recreates a field whose type
#     doesn't match the desired type (these are the script's own hardware
#     fields, repopulated every run), so the type is guaranteed. memory_gb is
#     now 'decimal' and sent as a number (e.g. 31.41), which is what it always
#     should have been for fractional GB. Added nb_delete().
#   - The per-field fallback now logs the actual NetBox error text, so any
#     remaining rejection says exactly why.
#   - NOTE (not a code bug): a wider scan now learns hosts on other VLANs via
#     SNMP ARP -- those become generic device-* entries (18 real responders +
#     ~10 ARP-only phantoms in the last capture). They are NOT VM IPs (verified:
#     zero overlap between any device-side IP and any VM primary IP, and VM-IP
#     coverage is identical to the earlier good run). An optional filter to skip
#     no-response ARP phantoms can be added on request.
#
