#  Changelog v2.5.10 (reverted to 2.5.9 baseline; isolated cable fix):
#   - Reverted the entire 2.6.x line (Phase C rewrite) after it caused a
#     cascade of regressions. 2.5.9 is the known-good base (working host-side
#     PS1, correct switch ID + Hyper-V hardware, SNMP ARP harvesting).
#   - LLDP/CDP cable fix (isolated): a neighbor's advertised port_id/port_desc
#     is the REMOTE device's port, not ours. It was being used to name the
#     LOCAL interface, so e.g. laundry-sw's 'g4' was added onto mancave-sw.
#     Now the advertised port terminates on the REMOTE device, and the local
#     side is a descriptive 'uplink-<neighbor>' (the container LLDP data does
#     not include our own local port; resolving it precisely needs the
#     SNMP LLDP-MIB local-port walk, deferred to a separate step).
#   - KNOWN/OPEN (next, by design): sync_to_netbox still syncs RAW results,
#     not the reconciled model, so .2 is not folded into .253 and the PS1
#     writes VMs on an uncoordinated path (no VM IPs, no device/VM dedup).
#     Planned fix: PS1 emits a JSON payload (read-only) pulled via WinRM and
#     fed to the reconciler, with a single coordinated writer.
#
#  Changelog v2.6.6 (correct LLDP cabling + multiple collection fallbacks):
#   ROOT CAUSE of the mis-assigned cable: an LLDP neighbor's advertised
#   port_id is the REMOTE device's port (e.g. laundry-sw's 'g4'), but the
#   code used it to name the LOCAL interface -- so 'g4' was added to the
#   wrong switch. The actual local port lives in the LLDP-MIB row index,
#   which the KaSaNaa container discards.
#   Collection now has THREE fallbacks, not SSH-only (most devices have no
#   SSH), in priority order:
#    1. Host-side lldpd over SSH (lldpctl/lldpcli keyvalue) -- Linux hosts;
#       gives local interface + remote name/port directly.
#    2. Supplementary SNMP LLDP-MIB walk (_snmp_walk_n, numeric OIDs):
#       lldpRemSysName/PortId/ChassisId joined with lldpLocPortId via the
#       localPortNum in the row index -> the LOCAL port is finally known for
#       SNMP devices (switches/gateway). This is how 2.5.8 collected, now
#       with the local side resolved.
#    3. Container lldp_neighbors/cdp_neighbors (remote-only) as a last
#       resort.
#   The cable loop normalizes all sources to {local_port, remote_name,
#   remote_mac, remote_port}, then: resolves the remote device by name ->
#   short name -> chassis MAC; puts the remote port on the REMOTE device;
#   and attaches the LOCAL side to the real local port when known, else a
#   clearly-named 'uplink-<remote>' (never the remote port). Reuses existing
#   interfaces (idempotent by name) instead of duplicating them.
# 
#  Changelog v2.6.5 (three issues from the live sync):
#   1. DISK FIELDS for 8 drives: the disk_N_* custom fields were always
#      created for 0..7. Now only as many sets as the busiest host actually
#      has are created (max hw_physical_disks count across hosts, capped 8),
#      so unused disk_N fields are not littered into NetBox.
#   2. SWITCH 192.168.0.52 missing everything: SNMP discovery SUCCEEDED for
#      it (TRACE) but the KaSaNaa->contract mapper returned available:false
#      because a stray non-JSON line on stdout broke a whole-file json.load.
#      The mapper now tolerates noisy output, falling back to the largest
#      {...} span, so a transient warning line no longer discards all SNMP
#      data (interfaces, LLDP, etc.) for that switch.
#   3. LLDP cables missing on nearly all devices: SNMP LLDP-MIB reports most
#      neighbors with an EMPTY sys_name and only a chassis/port MAC, so the
#      name-only lookup matched almost nothing. Added nb_device_by_mac() and
#      a MAC fallback in the cable loop: when there is no usable name, the
#      neighbor's chassis/port MAC is matched to the NetBox interface that
#      owns it (via the 4.x mac-addresses object model) and the cable is run
#      to that existing interface. NOTE: SNMP-based LLDP is inherently poorer
#      than host-side lldpd (which advertises real names); full-fidelity
#      topology still benefits from an on-host agent.
#
#  Changelog v2.6.4 (restore host hardware custom fields from the old PS1):
#   The legacy importer set per-DEVICE hardware custom fields on the physical
#   Hyper-V hosts (collected via Get-PhysicalDisk + ComputerSystem), which
#   went away when the PS1 was retired. These are 'the custom fields beyond
#   Discovered Ports' on the Hyper-V hosts. Restored end-to-end:
#   - PS_BASE now collects PhysicalDisks[] (SizeGB/Media/Interface via
#     Get-PhysicalDisk, falling back to Win32_DiskDrive) and
#     LogicalProcessors. (~5.9k encoded, still under the 8191 cmd-line cap.)
#   - merge_host_data carries hw_cpu_model/hw_os_version/hw_vcpus/
#     hw_memory_mb/hw_memory_gb/hw_physical_disks onto the host record; the
#     reconciler's enrich() preserves them onto the canonical dual-homed host.
#   - sync_to_netbox ensures the custom fields (vcpus, memory_mb, memory_gb,
#     disk_total_gb, disk_count, os_version, cpu_model, and disk_0..disk_7
#     size_gb/media/interface) and patches them onto each device that reports
#     WinRM hardware. Per-disk fields cap at 8 disks. Patch failures are
#     logged (Device HW CF patch failed ...).
#   - VM disk detail remains the native virtualization/virtual-disks objects
#     from v2.6.3; these device-level disk_* fields describe the physical
#     server, not the guests.
# 
#  Changelog v2.6.3 (virtual disks + custom-field read-back diagnostics):
#   - VIRTUAL DISKS (were not created): setting only the VM 'disk' field does
#     not populate the Disk column on NetBox 4.x -- that total is aggregated
#     from virtualization/virtual-disks/ objects. PS_HYPERV now collects a
#     per-VHD size array (Disks[]); the reconciler carries vm_disks; new
#     nb_sync_virtual_disk() creates one disk object per VHD
#     (<vmname>-disk<N>, size in GB). When only the legacy total is present
#     (capture predating per-disk collection) a single -disk0 is created from
#     it, so disks appear immediately and gain per-disk detail next capture.
#   - CUSTOM FIELDS: the device and VM custom-field patches now READ BACK the
#     stored value and log 'discovery_methods did not persist' with the
#     actual stored custom_fields if it didn't stick. The earlier-version log
#     showed both field scopes updating and no patch failures, so this pins
#     down whether the value is being rejected NetBox-side and why.
#   - NOTE: NetBox VirtualDisk.size is written in GB (matching the historical
#     importer + how VM.disk aggregates). If disk sizes read ~1000x off,
#     that's the one knob to flip to MB.
