#  Changelog v2.5.9 (Phase C prep -- printer page fix + VM IP recovery):
#   - probe_nmap(): port 9100 (raw JetDirect) is stripped from the -sV/NSE
#     deep scan so no payload is sent to it -- some printers (HP) eject a
#     garbage page when 9100 is banner-probed. 9100 stays in found_ports and
#     is unioned into the open-port list, so Printer classification is
#     unchanged. If 9100 is the only open port, the deep scan is skipped.
#   - reconcile_results(): an inverse MAC->IP map (from the SNMP ARP and
#     Hyper-V neighbor tables) now recovers the guest IP of an active VM that
#     reported none via Get-VMNetworkAdapter -- its vNIC MAC is looked up in
#     the gateway/host ARP tables (vm_ip_source='arp-recovered'). Any ACTIVE
#     (Running) VM still without a resolvable IP is flagged (vm_no_ip_flag)
#     and listed in the preview, so every active VM either gets an IP or is
#     surfaced for follow-up.
# 
#  Changelog v2.5.8 (THE actual WinRM root cause: command line too long):
#   - winrm.json revealed it: status=1 'The command line is too long.' This
#     was never transient. pywinrm.run_ps base64-encodes the script and runs
#     powershell -EncodedCommand via cmd.exe, whose command line caps at 8191
#     chars. As VM enumeration (v2.5.1) and the neighbor table (v2.5.4) were
#     added, the encoded PS_DISCOVER reached ~9520 chars -- over the cap -- so
#     EVERY WinRM call failed and the whole result was discarded (hosts ->
#     Workstation, 0 VMs from inventory). It worked in early runs only because
#     the script was smaller then.
#   - Fix: split PS_DISCOVER into two scripts run separately over the same
#     session -- PS_BASE (CIM/NICs/IsHyperV, always) and PS_HYPERV (VM
#     inventory + Get-NetNeighbor, only when IsHyperV). Each encodes to well
#     under the cap (~3.8k / ~3.5k). Their JSON is merged so HyperVVMs and
#     NeighborTable populate exactly as before. A per-step hyperv_error is
#     also captured. This restores Server roles, the full VM inventory, the
#     synthesized VMs and VM<->host attribution.
# 
#  Changelog v2.5.7 (WinRM reliability + diagnostics):
#   - The ping-sweep was NOT the cause of the WinRM failures (v2.5.4 ran with
#     the sweep and WinRM worked). Real likely cause: probe_winrm used a 30s
#     operation timeout and enumerated VM NICs PER VM (Get-VMNetworkAdapter
#     -VM $vm in a loop), which on hosts with 9-11 VMs intermittently blew
#     the timeout -- and every error was swallowed silently, so the whole
#     WinRM result was lost (hosts -> Workstation, 0 VMs from inventory).
#   - Fixes: (a) enumerate ALL VM NICs in ONE call (Get-VMNetworkAdapter
#     -VMName *) grouped by VM, far faster; (b) raise operation/read timeouts
#     to 120s/130s; (c) CAPTURE the failure reason into winrm.json as
#     winrm_error (status+stderr or exception) instead of swallowing it, so
#     the cause is visible in the raw capture if it still fails.
#   - Degraded mode remains: even with no WinRM, the SNMP ARP table + 00:15:5d
#     OUI fallback still tag every on-LAN VM (incl .235); WinRM adds the
#     synthesized off-LAN/powered-off VMs, Server roles, and host attribution.
# 
#  Changelog v2.5.6 (CRITICAL fix: ping-sweep was killing the WinRM probe):
#   - The v2.5.4 Hyper-V ping-sweep used [Task]::WaitAll($tasks) with NO
#     timeout, positioned between Get-VM and the JSON output. When ICMP was
#     filtered (common on hardened hosts) the async pings never completed,
#     WaitAll blocked until the WinRM operation timed out, and the script
#     never emitted its JSON -- so the ENTIRE WinRM result was lost. Symptom:
#     SERVER01/03/04 fell back to Workstation, 0 VMs synthesized from
#     inventory, and VMs only matched via the 00:15:5d OUI fallback.
#   - Removed the ping sweep entirely. It is redundant now that the SNMP ARP
#     table (v2.5.5) supplies LAN-wide IP->MAC. probe_winrm keeps only an
#     instant, safe Get-NetNeighbor read of the existing cache as a bonus.
#     Restores the full VM inventory, Server roles, and VM<->host links while
#     .235 etc. still resolve via the SNMP ARP table.
# 
#  Changelog v2.5.5 (SNMP ARP-table IP->MAC harvesting):
#   - probe_snmp(): after a successful SNMP probe, walk the device's ARP/
#     neighbor table -- the classic AT table (1.3.6.1.2.1.3.1.1.2) and the
#     modern ipNetToMediaPhysAddress (1.3.6.1.2.1.4.22.1.2) -- and emit
#     IP->MAC pairs (last four OID octets = IPv4, Hex-STRING = MAC). A
#     router/firewall/gateway holds the WHOLE subnet's IP->MAC in one walk,
#     so this resolves MACs for every host at once, not just Hyper-V VMs.
#     The working v2c/v3 credential is reused via _snmp_walk. Read-only.
#   - merge_host_data(): the harvested table is attached as host['arp_table'].
#   - reconcile_results(): the MAC backfill now folds in BOTH sources --
#     Hyper-V Get-NetNeighbor tables AND SNMP arp_table entries -- before VM
#     matching, so a record the L2-blind scanner saw with no MAC (e.g. .235)
#     is resolved from whichever L3/hypervisor device knows it, then bound to
#     its VM. This is more general than the Hyper-V-only path (one gateway
#     walk covers the entire LAN) and the two sources are complementary.
# 
#  Changelog v2.5.4 (Hyper-V neighbor-table MAC resolution):
#   - Root cause found: the scanner has NO L2 adjacency to the LAN (it runs
#     in a NAT'd container), so it never learns MAC addresses -- nmap -Pn
#     captures none and the kernel ARP cache stays empty. Scanner-side MAC
#     capture is impossible here; .235 (CLI SysLog Server VM, no guest IP
#     reported) therefore had no key to bind to its VM.
#   - probe_winrm(): each Hyper-V host now ping-sweeps its local /24 and
#     returns its Get-NetNeighbor IP->MAC table as NeighborTable[]. A
#     hypervisor is L2-adjacent to its VMs on the vSwitch, so it resolves
#     the vNIC MAC the scanner cannot see. Read-only; no NetBox calls.
#   - merge_host_data(): NeighborTable copied onto host['neighbor_table'].
#   - reconcile_results(): before VM matching, builds a global IP->MAC map
#     from all Hyper-V neighbor tables and fills a MAC onto any record that
#     has none. discovered-IP -> MAC (neighbor) -> VM (inventory) then binds
#     .235 to the Running CLI SysLog Server on SERVER01 with no duplicate;
#     the Off replica remains its own VM on SERVER04.
# 
#  Changelog v2.5.3 (robust ARP MAC capture + deterministic enriched merge):
#   - scan_single_host(): the host MAC is now read from the LIVE kernel
#     neighbor/ARP cache (ip neigh / arp -n) right AFTER probing, when a
#     same-subnet host is resolved even if nmap used -Pn and recorded no
#     MAC. The Phase-1 arp_map is only a fallback. Fixes 192.168.0.235 (the
#     CLI SysLog Server VM: auto-named, nmap-only, no guest IP) which had no
#     MAC at all in the prior run, so it could not bind to its VM and showed
#     as a duplicate device. The earlier Phase-1-only map produced zero
#     captures because the cache is not populated until Phase-2 traffic.
#   - reconcile_results(): canonical record selection is now DETERMINISTIC --
#     lowest IP wins, except (a) an ip_table secondary (192.168.0.2) can
#     never win over its owner (.253) and (b) a real name beats an auto-name.
#     Crucially the survivor is now ENRICHED from the records it absorbs:
#     is_hyperv, hyperv_vms, winrm_nics, the strongest device_role, missing
#     identity fields, SNMP OID, best scan_tier and unioned interfaces. This
#     fixes dual-homed Hyper-V hosts whose WinRM/VM data lives on only one IP
#     (SERVER03 .243/.245): the canonical .243 keeps Server + Hyper-V + all
#     its VMs instead of degrading to a bare Windows Workstation.
#   - NOTE: .5/.51 role flips between runs are scan variance (SNMP/SSH not
#     answering that pass), not a classifier regression.
#
#  Changelog v2.5.2 (ARP-MAC propagation + replica-correct VM binding):
#   - Phase-1 discovery now records an IP->MAC map (arp_map.txt) from
#     arp-scan and the ARP cache (ip neigh / arp -n); arp_lookup() + a new
#     $tmp/arp.json injected per host so nmap-only hosts that capture no MAC
#     still carry one. merge_host_data sets host['mac'] from ARP when nmap
#     has none; the reconciler's host_macs() now also reads the top-level
#     MAC. Fixes 192.168.0.235 (CLI SysLog Server VM, auto-named, no scanned
#     MAC, no guest IP reported) which previously could not be matched to a
#     VM and showed as a duplicate device.
#   - Hyper-V Replica VMs are NOT collapsed: a primary and its replica are
#     two separate VMs on their two hosts. Because a Running primary and its
#     Off replica can share a MAC, a discovered live IP that matches several
#     instances binds to the RUNNING one (the replica is Off and is not
#     serving that IP); the replica remains its own VM record. Synthetic VM
#     keys are de-collided so two same-named VMs (a VM and its replica copy)
#     on different hosts don't clash. VM instances on dual-homed hosts are
#     counted once (the merged secondary IP is skipped before VM resolution).
# 
#  Changelog v2.5.1 (Phase B -- Hyper-V VM inventory in reconciliation):
#   - probe_winrm(): the WinRM discovery PS now enumerates VMs READ-ONLY on
#     Hyper-V hosts (Get-VM + Get-VMNetworkAdapter): per-VM name/state/vCPU/
#     memory and per-adapter MAC/IPs/switch, returned as HyperVVMs[] in the
#     existing JSON. No NetBox calls; nothing installed on the host.
#   - merge_host_data(): HyperVVMs copied onto the host record as hyperv_vms.
#   - reconcile_results(): now builds a global VM inventory from every
#     Hyper-V host and (a) MATCHES discovered devices to a VM by MAC (then
#     IP/name) -> sync_as=vm with vm_host/vm_cluster so a VM that is also
#     discovered resolves to a single VM ON ITS HOST; (b) SYNTHESIZES records
#     for VMs that were not independently IP-scanned so every VM is captured;
#     (c) keeps the 00:15:5d OUI heuristic as a fallback. A hardware SNMP OID
#     (not the generic Net-SNMP 8072 tree) blocks IP/name VM-matching so a
#     physical switch/printer/AP can't be mislabeled a VM by a reused IP.
#   - Reason: the discovery probe previously only detected IsHyperV and never
#     enumerated VMs, so reconciliation saw only VMs that were both IP-scanned
#     and exposed a Hyper-V MAC -- missing most VMs and all VM<->host links.
# 
#  Changelog v2.5.0 (Phase B step 1 -- reconciler core + dry-run preview):
#   - NEW reconcile_results(): collapses cross-host duplicates in a
#     results_*.json into a canonical device/VM model BEFORE syncing. Pure
#     data transform (embedded Python, no NetBox calls), writes
#     <results>.reconciled.json. Union-find merge passes (transitive):
#       1. SNMP ip_table ownership -- a secondary IP folds into its owner
#          (192.168.0.2 -> 192.168.0.253), no more phantom device.
#       2. shared interface MAC.
#       3. normalized short hostname (FQDN<->NetBIOS<->dual-homed), with a
#          generic-name denylist so two 'iPhone' devices stay separate while
#          dual-homed SERVER03/SERVER04 still merge.
#     Richest record wins identity; losers -> secondary_ips + sync_as=skip.
#   - VM tagging: a Hyper-V OUI (00:15:5d) interface MAC on a non-hypervisor
#     record sets sync_as=vm (OPNsense/pfSense/FortiManager/FortiAnalyzer),
#     so a VM that is also discovered as a device resolves to a single VM.
#   - Main menu option 8 'Preview Reconciliation' -- dry-run plan, no writes.
#   - NOTE: sync_to_netbox does NOT yet consume the reconciled file; that is
#     the next Phase B step after the preview is validated on a live scan.
